06:29.800 --> 06:33.680
There are subcategories coming under the general headings of science fiction and fantasy.

06:34.200 --> 06:36.960
One of the most popular these days is heroic fantasy.

06:37.460 --> 06:42.140
It's sometimes called sword and sorcery, a term that almost serves as a definition for the genre.

06:42.140 --> 06:47.960
It deals with heroic barbarians swinging large bloody swords and sorcerers conjuring up all manner of demons.

06:48.560 --> 06:53.460
And as we've said, it's popular nowadays, particularly the Conan stories of Robert E. Howard.

06:54.020 --> 06:59.760
We asked an authority on heroic fantasy, L. Spray De Camp, to tell us why the form is so fascinating to readers.

07:00.360 --> 07:11.460
I think that part of the popularity of the genre was a reaction to certain trends in fiction

07:11.460 --> 07:24.960
following the Second World War, such as the fondness for heavily subjective psychological or psychiatric stories.

07:26.440 --> 07:34.600
Very sentimental stories, stories glorifying the little man, the anti-hero, you know,

07:34.600 --> 07:41.660
that hopeless little jerk who can't do anything right and who has no brains or brawn or character

07:41.660 --> 07:43.860
and whose only function is to suffer and suffer.

07:44.580 --> 07:48.140
Well, I think people got sort of tired of that after a while.

07:48.460 --> 07:54.960
So they, then, between the paperback publication of the Conan stories,

07:55.200 --> 07:58.240
for which I can claim the credit, I'm the one who sold them,

07:58.240 --> 08:03.140
and the paperback publication of Tolkien's Lord of the Rings,

08:03.460 --> 08:08.280
which was the other major factor in launching this boom,

08:08.840 --> 08:17.040
why that got people to reading heroic fantasy on a large scale, which they are still doing.

08:28.300 --> 08:33.460
De Camp has written his own sword and sorcery, but he's also worked on the Conan material of Robert E. Howard.

08:33.920 --> 08:36.480
He tells us how he was introduced to Howard's stories of Conan.

08:37.720 --> 08:49.420
I went up to New York in, it was around the end of 1950, and let me see, I think it was a naval war game at Pratt's apartment

08:49.420 --> 08:52.420
or something, no it wasn't, it was a party at Pratt's apartment.

08:53.420 --> 09:00.600
And he handed me a copy of Conan the Conqueror, Bound in Hardback, published by Noam Press.

09:01.680 --> 09:08.340
And he said, here, take this so long, I think you might find it interesting, I don't care much for it myself, but who knows.

09:09.000 --> 09:17.580
So I took it, it seems that Martin had, by inadvertence, sent Fletcher to review copies, and Fletcher gave me one.

09:17.580 --> 09:21.780
I started reading it on the train going home and was hooked right away.

09:23.080 --> 09:26.420
Kept on until I read the thing through and then I read it through again.

09:27.580 --> 09:32.180
Howard died in the 1930s, but De Camp became so involved with the character of Conan

09:32.180 --> 09:36.120
that he started to edit some of Howard's papers and to write his own Conan stories.

09:37.110 --> 09:50.740
And then a year later, I learned about some unpublished Conan manuscripts in the custody of the agent for the Howard Literary Estate.

09:51.620 --> 10:02.800
And I read them and arrangements were made with the Howard Ayers and the agent for me to edit them and arrange for publication.

10:02.800 --> 10:09.740
And then on, things have gone on and on and built up from that.

10:13.140 --> 10:23.200
De Camp has written original Conan material, but he's also finished incomplete Howard's stories and edited others.

10:23.880 --> 10:27.920
De Camp is also technical advisor to a movie on Conan that will premiere this week.

10:27.920 --> 10:32.920
It's entitled Conan the Barbarian, and it will show you what heroic fantasy is all about.

