12:10.780 --> 12:13.620
Robert E. Howard, the creator of Conan the Barbarian, was a paradox.

12:14.240 --> 12:16.840
He was brought up on the arid plains of west central Texas,

12:17.300 --> 12:19.380
lived in the small country town of cross plains,

12:19.560 --> 12:20.800
and hardly did any traveling.

12:21.180 --> 12:23.580
And he died by his own hand at the age of 30.

12:24.080 --> 12:26.940
Yet Howard wrote heroic stories that were set in the mythical age

12:26.940 --> 12:28.120
after the fall of Atlantis.

12:28.640 --> 12:31.220
He was fascinated with the misty, cold northern landscape

12:31.220 --> 12:32.440
in which he set his tales.

12:33.140 --> 12:36.060
Conan, his greatest creation, was a barbarian from the north,

12:36.480 --> 12:40.180
a giant who strode across the Hyborian age, wielding a bloody broadsword.

12:40.500 --> 12:42.000
But Howard's life was a quiet one.

12:42.540 --> 12:44.580
He was introverted, bookish, and shy.

12:45.100 --> 12:47.800
As far as we know, he was never in a brawl or fight of any kind.

12:48.360 --> 12:52.020
Why did Howard create Conan and place him in a mythical northern landscape?

12:52.540 --> 12:55.160
What sort of mind would conceive of a barbarian hero,

12:55.160 --> 12:57.240
a loner who spurns civilization?

12:57.560 --> 12:59.480
We spoke with Dr. Charlotte Laughlin,

12:59.720 --> 13:02.120
a professor at Howard Payne University in Brownwood, Texas,

13:02.560 --> 13:04.580
not far from Howard's home in cross plains.

13:05.000 --> 13:06.900
Dr. Laughlin is intimate with Howard's life

13:06.900 --> 13:09.000
and has done research for a Howard biography.

13:09.560 --> 13:12.540
She believes there are some reasons for Howard's obsession with Conan.

13:13.620 --> 13:18.720
I think that again, it was a sort of explanation for why he did not fit in with other people.

13:18.860 --> 13:21.640
He liked to believe I am the last barbarian.

13:21.640 --> 13:24.660
It's because in my type, Will Preveille,

13:25.320 --> 13:29.000
he liked to believe that the other people had a veneer of civilization on them

13:29.000 --> 13:32.000
that got them away from the basics that were really important.

13:32.420 --> 13:35.200
And if you've read his correspondence with Lovecraft,

13:35.580 --> 13:42.480
they had long arguments about the physical versus the intellectual needs of a society.

13:43.080 --> 13:46.420
And Howard would say that in the tough country where he lived,

13:46.520 --> 13:49.160
you had to be physically fit, and he spent a great deal of his life,

13:49.160 --> 13:51.860
his adult life trying to be physically fit,

13:52.620 --> 13:56.140
boxing and working out and that sort of thing.

14:02.540 --> 14:05.640
Howard also was fascinated with the legendary past of Britain,

14:06.060 --> 14:09.360
especially with the savage Picks and the early heroes of Celtic myth.

14:09.920 --> 14:12.440
Some of his Conan stories, such as Across the Dark River,

14:12.820 --> 14:14.320
have ancient Britain as their setting.

14:14.840 --> 14:18.260
We asked Dr. Loughlin why Howard was so drawn to this material.

14:19.100 --> 14:23.100
He claimed that he was full blood Irish and they were the Irish kings,

14:23.280 --> 14:25.100
like some other people we know claim to be.

14:25.600 --> 14:28.600
But there's no evidence that he certainly was not full blood Irish.

14:28.720 --> 14:33.600
People have traced his genealogy, but this was part of his image of himself.

14:33.780 --> 14:37.140
He was trying to project other people and trying to create for himself.

14:38.400 --> 14:42.200
There again he wrote at one time that he wrote about the barren, cold,

14:43.320 --> 14:47.660
windswept, damp areas, even though he lived here.

14:47.940 --> 14:50.140
I think that again might be a sort of wish fulfillment

14:50.140 --> 14:53.720
who wouldn't like to be someplace where it's cold on a day like this.

14:53.920 --> 14:58.080
He wanted to be away from where he was because I don't think we can underestimate

14:58.080 --> 15:03.540
the anger and frustration that was boiling around in Robert Howard all the time.

15:03.540 --> 15:10.540
I see it in all of his poetry and a great deal of his fiction.

15:11.540 --> 15:13.920
Cross Plains neighbors say that he had a...

15:13.920 --> 15:18.500
There was a big tree stump out by his yard and I believe it was a sledgehammer, not an axe.

15:18.900 --> 15:21.380
And sometimes in the middle of the day he would go out there,

15:21.500 --> 15:23.000
you know, and you could just see that he was so tense

15:23.460 --> 15:28.080
and he would take that sledgehammer and he would just wham it and wham it and wham it on this tree stump.

15:28.880 --> 15:32.980
That a tremendous amount of anger he didn't fit in with other people,

15:32.980 --> 15:38.800
he wanted to be somewhere else, so he wrote about something that was like nothing he had experienced.

15:45.740 --> 15:50.540
Howard wrote Reams of Fantasy and the Pulp Era of the 1930s, most of it for weird tales.

15:51.120 --> 15:53.240
We asked Dr. Loughlin why Howard wrote Fantasy.

15:53.700 --> 15:57.880
Did he have the talent to write more realistic fiction that might have gotten him out of the Pulp Ghetto?

15:58.940 --> 16:03.560
He may have had the talent, but I certainly don't believe he was capable of writing realistic fiction.

16:04.040 --> 16:07.200
He was not that closely tied to reality himself.

16:07.800 --> 16:12.500
I don't believe he ever could have written realistic novels. He had to write fantasies of some sort.

