17:51.320 --> 17:57.660
Fantasy writer Robert E. Howard grew up in the 1920s and the 1930s in the small Texas town of Cross Plains.

17:58.040 --> 18:01.520
But he wasn't like other small town boys. He kept to himself quite a bit.

18:01.960 --> 18:05.780
He read a lot and used a vivid imagination to create his memorable heroic fantasies,

18:06.380 --> 18:09.080
for most of which are the stories of Conan the Barbarian.

18:09.560 --> 18:14.260
Howard died in 1936, but some of the people in Cross Plains still remember him clearly.

18:14.820 --> 18:18.920
We spoke with two of Howard's friends, Jack Scott, the editor of the Cross Plains newspaper,

18:19.500 --> 18:21.520
and Leroy Butler, Howard's next door neighbor.

18:22.080 --> 18:24.700
Butler remembers a time when he and Howard were still children,

18:24.980 --> 18:27.720
and they bought some swords from a mail order company in New York.

18:28.680 --> 18:33.260
But we ordered those things and we'd get out in the backyard and wrap a bandana

18:33.260 --> 18:39.900
around our hedge-like pirate, and we'd get out and fence with those things.

18:40.660 --> 18:46.280
Of course we didn't dare, you know, hit each other with them because they were, they'd have gone through you.

18:48.100 --> 18:52.820
But we did that quite a bit. We had an immense live oak tree in our backyard,

18:52.820 --> 18:56.040
and we'd get out there and shade that old tree in,

18:58.720 --> 19:04.320
pretend that we were back maybe in the dark ages or something,

19:05.840 --> 19:11.960
or in the time of the Spanish man, things like that.

19:12.700 --> 19:15.860
He had things like that on his mind all the time.

19:17.040 --> 19:20.280
Butler says that Robert was a loner dedicated to his writing.

19:21.280 --> 19:24.380
Robert never married, he never seemed interested in girls,

19:27.520 --> 19:31.340
and he did have one girlfriend there in Cross Plains for a time.

19:31.440 --> 19:34.180
I'd see him out in the car driving around once in a while,

19:35.000 --> 19:37.160
but I don't think that lasted long.

19:37.940 --> 19:42.800
He was just wrapped up in his, in his work writing those stories,

19:44.840 --> 19:51.080
and he had a blast-in-back porch on the southeast side of the house there,

19:52.680 --> 19:55.720
and it wasn't too far from my mother's bedroom,

19:57.520 --> 20:01.440
and a lot of times at night he'd wake her up with that typewriter clock,

20:01.640 --> 20:03.480
and you know, at 1 or 2 o'clock in the morning.

20:04.560 --> 20:08.980
Some inspiration, he'd probably be laying there in bed and think of something,

20:09.080 --> 20:11.260
and he'd get up and write it down right quick.

20:14.200 --> 20:16.000
And he just worked all hours.

20:17.840 --> 20:20.620
Jack Scott also comments on Howard's unusual personality.

20:21.460 --> 20:25.800
Howard was a little on the, a little, little on the odd side.

20:25.900 --> 20:27.700
He wasn't in them, but there was very many people,

20:27.820 --> 20:31.140
and he was rather in a loop, but he was a big robust man.

20:31.820 --> 20:36.800
To me, he was a combination of, uh, Edgar Allen Poe and Jack London,

20:37.040 --> 20:38.980
if you can imagine that two together.

20:40.140 --> 20:43.760
In 1936, when Howard's mother was dying of a terminal illness,

20:44.180 --> 20:45.360
Howard took his own life.

20:46.340 --> 20:50.600
I remember, I remember the morning he, he killed himself very well.

20:51.520 --> 20:54.380
I heard on the street that Robert Howard had just shot himself,

20:54.700 --> 20:58.300
and I immediately jumped in my car and ran down there,

20:58.560 --> 21:01.940
and got down there, and a few neighbors had gathered.

21:02.880 --> 21:05.380
Uh, it wasn't generally known over town, but, uh,

21:05.380 --> 21:12.140
the old justice of the peace was standing there on the, on the, uh, gallery, the front porch,

21:12.680 --> 21:14.400
and when I walked up, he called and said,

21:14.440 --> 21:18.040
come here, Jack, and I stepped up there, and he took me into the bedroom,

21:18.800 --> 21:22.420
and he, he pointed to an old Underwood typewriter,

21:22.640 --> 21:24.860
and he's had four lines written on it there,

21:25.620 --> 21:30.640
and Howard had, had, uh, when he had been told that his mother wouldn't,

21:30.640 --> 21:33.620
uh, wouldn't live throughout the day,

21:33.620 --> 21:37.060
uh, he went to this typewriter, wrote these four lines,

21:37.060 --> 21:40.140
walked outside, and sat down his car and shot his head off,

21:40.880 --> 21:44.800
and this old J.P. asked me what these four lines meant, meant.

21:45.760 --> 21:48.460
They said, I'm sure you've read them all, fled all done,

21:48.460 --> 21:52.460
so let me on the tire, the feast is over, the lamps expire.

